Some people very legitimately feel that the public authority should also be the provider of services.
I agree with my colleague, Mr HÃ¶kmark, that the market can provide excellent services.
Some sectors have been liberalised and that did not mean that more people were excluded from access to those services, but quite the contrary: many services have come within reach of many more people, which is extremely social.
A market is not a jungle; it has rules, because if there are no rules it is not a market.
Any market â even the simplest market on the market square â has rules and that is exactly what we mean by the social market economy we have in Europe.
We need to recognise the diversity of the Member States and allow them to decide for themselves what they call âservices of general interestâ.
Finally, we should not try to define what services of general interest and services of general economic interest are, because the word âeconomicâ applies not to the nature of the service itself but to the way in which it is provided.
To take an example: everybody will recognise that water is of general interest, but it may be provided in a purely commercial way.
So we must not lose ourselves in a senseless debate on the differences between âof general interestâ and âgeneral economic interestâ.
The only interest we should be looking at here is the interest of our citizens and consumers.
